fields.description:
IOT Training:

Day -1: All about IOT
What is IOT?
Why do we need IOT?
Applications of IOT
Case Study- Smart City through Video demo and slides
IOT Control system(App control,web control)
IOT Control Devices(NodeMCU)
Day-2: Arduino and arduino Programming
Introduction to arduino
Its microcontroller and working
 Arduino Programming:
IDE setup
Basic arduino program structure or format
Code flow
Different libraries

Day-3:Demo Projects:
Different Components and interfacing
Led blinking
Potentiometer value reading and displaying
LDR value reading and displaying and further applications(like person counter, attendance system)
DTH11 sensor interfacing and displaying temp and hum
Day-4:App controlled IOT(Blynk app):
Blynk app installation and widgets creation(Led button,Fan button,Temp & Hum Display widget)
App setup in arduino program code

Day-5: Web Controlled IOT(ACESS PART)
Buttons creation, display board for temp and humidity  -->Front End
API making, database creation,table creation, data entry etc
GET/POST requests
Data posting and retrieving commands from server in arduino code

Day-6: Project one(Home Automation)
Light Control(based on light intensity(LDR))
Fan Control(Temp controlled)
Data logger(Temp and Humidity)
Door locking system
Day-7: Google Assistant Implementation in project one

fields.name: Hello maya how are you?
fields.description:
How a habit is formed? And how long does it take to form a new habit?
Published on April 2, 2020
Edit article
View stats
Razz SawhoneyStatus is online
Razz Sawhoney
Python Django Developer | Good Hands on C/C++ | AI & ML Aspirant | Image Processing | NLP | Computer Vision|Fluttering
1 article
To answer the above questions, I had put myself under a test for 21 days. It was more like a research(informal type) for me. The test was basically based on the following objectives:

To check the validity of the fact that ”It takes 21 days to form a new habit”.
How to completely eliminate any of your habits (bad ones) from your life?
How long does it take to remove old & bad habits and form a new one?
To discover the various factors behind the present young generation problem i.e Sleepiness.
To discover the best possible ways to form a good and new habit.


NOO!!!

At the end of my test, I got a big NO for the very first objective.

No, it does not take 21 days.

In fact, it is either done in a split second or never.

Why? Because a habit in its basic form is a neural sequence hard-coded in your brain. Let’s assume your brain as a memory card or hard disk drive and your habits(especially in this context) and various other things else as data stored in it. Let me consider an example to make it more clear to you. Let H1, H2, H3 be your three habits(data) stored in your hard disk(brain). And you want to get rid of habit H2 because that’s a bad one for you and you want to form a new one in that place. The only way to make that possible is to override it with new data i.e new habit. But it’s not that simple as is in case of memory read/write/update operation.

However, in the case of human beings, the same protocol is not followed which is followed in case of memory card or hard disk drive. You cannot break your habits, I mean you cannot remove them completely from your life. The only thing you can do is manipulate them. More clearly if a habit is a pattern saved in your brain, you can "overwrite" this pattern with a new behavior in a new fashion or way.

And before you learn how to override an old bad habit with a new habit, first of all, you need to understand how a habit is stored in your brain. It is saved in your neurons as a habit loop that consists of three elements: a cue(like time and condition-based recursive function call in any programming language) that triggers a routine; a routine that follows the trigger; and an endpoint that finishes the loop.

A cue can be anything like a place, time of the day, your emotional state, even words or specific events. What is more, because of the associative nature of our memory, very often the cue is the set of specific conditions. If you are bored at work, it will trigger different behavior than being bored at home.

Changing the trigger is impossible. The same set of conditions when met will always start the habit loop. For example, we all generally over-sleep on Saturday because we know its holiday and similarly we over-sleep when it’s raining in the morning or it has rained last night. So here the holiday, the rain, etc are conditions responsible for triggering our habit loop. But it's not so, that you cannot change it or get rid of it. Obviously, you can get rid of it. It's all mind play. Your brain(mind) is responsible for all these funky behaviors. In order to beat your mind, you have to dodge it. Yes, you read it right. We have to dodge our brain(mind). We have to play a game with our minds. We have to lure our brains for something very interesting and something very satisfying. If you want to override any of your habits which you don’t like with an entirely new one, then try to put some good & strong reason behind it, some kind of achievements which you're gonna achieve after you do so. This trick is really helpful, at least for me as it worked very well in my case and I’m damn sure that it’s gonna work for everyone else case too. See our brain and heart are like a little kid and we better know how to handle a kid. Simply lure your kid with some attracting sweets or dolls or anything which your kid is gonna like and get attracted. All I mean is you have to set some genuine goal, a genuine reason behind any of your habits you want to form. Only then you can override any of your existing habits with a brand new one. And trust me it's not gonna take you 21 days to form that habit or to make that habit a part of your life. I don’t say so rather my experience says so. I always used to wake up at about 9-10 AM, but a radical change came to me in just 2-3 days of my test. All I did to change myself was a very sweet and attractive reason set behind.

Leave it here and let me talk on my next objective of my test i.e various factors responsible for the young generation sleeping problem.

Well, it’s quite obvious to everyone and it is practically true as well. You’re surely gonna wake up late in the day if you went for sleeping late at night. So, yes sleeping late at night is the primary reason behind this issue and there may be various reasons and factors involved behind this primary reason. The social media I guess lies top in the list. Yah, we young generation are like a veteran druggist at social media, Facebook coming first in the hit list and various others after it like Insta, TikTok, Likee, YouTube, WhatsApp, Viber, etc. We feel like, we just cannot live without them. In the present context, people feel like they are socially boycotted if they’re not available on social media. But the truth isn’t so. It’s simply their misconception and their wrong mindset. Instead of thinking so we can think like we are different from others if we are not available on social media and being different has its own joy. Only a person like me can understand it well.

Moving further Chatting unnecessarily on useless topics with the so-called virtual friends(Fb wala-wali,WhatsApp wala-wali ,Viber wala-wali) late at night is another notable factor. Playing mobile and desktop games like PUB-G, Free-Fire, EVE-Online, etc late at night are also responsible factors. Ohh how can I miss my fav i.e watching movies till the end one after another is another factor in the list. And the rests you can now add yourself to the list.

What did I end up my test for 21 days with (Benefits)??

Learned a lot about human behavior and emotions.
Factors affecting human behavior and emotions.
Best possible ways to override any existing behavior.
Active enough to wake up early in the morning at about 5 AM.
Built a habit of going jogging every morning and doing light exercises as my daily routine
Finds myself active and fit the whole day.
Summary:

I have already mentioned the best possible ways to eliminate any bad habits and build a new one. And now I just want to polish them a little in the summary part. You(the young generation) yourself are the best possible solution to this problem. Hack yourself i.e try to know your behavior and emotions in-depth, various triggers responsible for starting your habit loop and then eliminate those with the trick I mentioned above. Just don’t forget the verse “Dil aur Dimag toh bachcha hai Ji”,(a hindi saying meaning "brain and heart are like a little kids') and take necessary actions and tricks and play with them in the way you like.

equest and response objects¶
Quick overview¶
Django uses request and response objects to pass state through the system.

When a page is requested, Django creates an HttpRequest object that contains metadata about the request. Then Django loads the appropriate view, passing the HttpRequest as the first argument to the view function. Each view is responsible for returning an HttpResponse object.

This document explains the APIs for HttpRequest and HttpResponse objects, which are defined in the django.http module.

HttpRequest objects¶
class HttpRequest¶
Attributes¶
All attributes should be considered read-only, unless stated otherwise.

HttpRequest.scheme¶
A string representing the scheme of the request (http or https usually).

HttpRequest.body¶
The raw HTTP request body as a bytestring. This is useful for processing data in different ways than conventional HTML forms: binary images, XML payload etc. For processing conventional form data, use HttpRequest.POST.

You can also read from an HttpRequest using a file-like interface. See HttpRequest.read().

HttpRequest.path¶
A string representing the full path to the requested page, not including the scheme or domain.

Example: "/music/bands/the_beatles/"

HttpRequest.path_info¶
Under some Web server configurations, the portion of the URL after the host name is split up into a script prefix portion and a path info portion. The path_info attribute always contains the path info portion of the path, no matter what Web server is being used. Using this instead of path can make your code easier to move between test and deployment servers.

For example, if the WSGIScriptAlias for your application is set to "/minfo", then path might be "/minfo/music/bands/the_beatles/" and path_info would be "/music/bands/the_beatles/".
